To implement a RESTful API for an online bookstore using ASP.NET Core and Entity Framework with MySQL, follow these steps:

1. Install the necessary tools and packages
Ensure that you have .NET 5 or a more recent version installed. You will also need Visual Studio or Visual Studio Code as your IDE. Additionally, download and install MySQL for your platform.

2. Create a new ASP.NET Core Web API project
Open Visual Studio and create a new project. Select the "ASP.NET Core Web API" template, and click "Next". Name your project (e.g., "BookStoreAPI") and click "Create".

3. Add necessary NuGet packages
To work with Entity Framework Core and MySQL, you will need to install some NuGet packages. In the terminal or Package Manager Console, run the following commands:

```
Install-Package Pomelo.EntityFrameworkCore.MySql
Install-Package Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Proxies
```

4. Set up your database connection string
In your appsettings.json file, add the following connection string to configure your MySQL database:

```json
{
  "ConnectionStrings": {
    "BookStoreDbContext": "server=localhost;port=3306;database=BookStore;user=<username>;password=<password>"
  },
  ...
```

Replace `<username>` and `<password>` with your MySQL credentials.

5. Create your entity models
Create the following models to represent books, authors, and genres:

```csharp
public class Book
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Title { get; set; }
    public int AuthorId { get; set; }
    public Author Author { get; set; }
    public int GenreId { get; set; }
    public Genre Genre { get; set; }
    public decimal Price { get; set; }
    public int Quantity { get; set; }
}

public class Author
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public ICollection<Book> Books { get; set; }
}

public class Genre
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public ICollection<Book> Books { get; set; }
}
```

6. Set up Entity Framework DB context
Create a new class called "BookStoreDbContext" in a folder called "Data" and extend DbContext:

```csharp
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;
using BookStoreAPI.Models;

namespace BookStoreAPI.Data
{
    public class BookStoreDbContext : DbContext
    {
        public BookStoreDbContext(DbContextOptions<BookStoreDbContext> options) : base(options) { }

        public DbSet<Book> Books { get; set; }
        public DbSet<Author> Authors { get; set; }
        public DbSet<Genre> Genres { get; set; }

        // Configure entity relationships and properties
        protected override void OnModelCreating(ModelBuilder modelBuilder)
        {
            modelBuilder.Entity<Author>()
                .HasMany(a => a.Books)
                .WithOne(b => b.Author)
                .HasForeignKey(b => b.AuthorId);

            modelBuilder.Entity<Genre>()
                .HasMany(g => g.Books)
                .WithOne(b => b.Genre)
                .HasForeignKey(b => b.GenreId);

            // Additional configuration and seed data can be added here
        }
    }
}
```

7. Configure the services in Startup.cs
Register your DbContext and any required services in the ConfigureServices() method:

```csharp
using BookStoreAPI.Data;
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;
using Pomelo.EntityFrameworkCore.MySql.Infrastructure;

public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services)
{
    services.AddControllers();

    // Add DbContext and configure connection
    services.AddDbContextPool<BookStoreDbContext>(options =>
    {
        options.UseMySql(Configuration.GetConnectionString("BookStoreDbContext"),
            new MySqlServerVersion(new Version(8, 0, 21)),
            mySqlOptions => mySqlOptions.CharSetBehavior(CharSetBehavior.NeverAppend));
    });

    // Enable lazy-loading
    services.AddDbContext<BookStoreDbContext>(options =>
        options.UseLazyLoadingProxies());
}
```

8. Create the API controllers
Right-click your "Controllers" folder and create three separate new controllers named "BooksController", "AuthorsController", and "GenresController". In each of these controllers, implement the CRUD operations using Entity Framework and your BookStoreDbContext. You can use scaffolding to generate these controllers automatically with the necessary methods.

9. Test the API
Run the API and test each endpoint using a tool like Postman or Swagger. You should be able to perform CRUD operations on books, authors, and genres, as well as search for books by title, author, or genre.

