The error is occurring because a tracked instance of the `Genre` with the same primary key value already exists in the in-memory DbContext. When updating an entity, you are attempting to update it in the context while another instance with the same primary key is already being tracked.

To resolve this issue, you can opt to use the `AsNoTracking()` method to avoid tracking the `Genre` entity while retrieving it from the database. Update the `Setup()` method of your GenreControllerTests.cs file as follows:

```csharp
[SetUp]
public void Setup()
{
    // Create InMemory DbContext for testing
    var options = new DbContextOptionsBuilder<BookStoreDbContext>()
        .UseInMemoryDatabase(databaseName: "BookStoreTestDb")
        .Options;

    _context = new BookStoreDbContext(options);
    _controller = new GenresController(_context);

    // Seed test data
    _context.Genres.AddRange(
        new Genre { Id = 1, Name = "Fiction" },
        new Genre { Id = 2, Name = "Thriller" },
        new Genre { Id = 3, Name = "Romance" }
    );

    _context.SaveChanges();

    // Detach all tracked entities
    foreach (var entry in _context.ChangeTracker.Entries())
    {
        entry.State = EntityState.Detached;
    }
}
```

Here, we've added a loop after the `SaveChanges()` call to detach all tracked entities in the DbContext. This should prevent the conflict from occurring when trying to update the Genre entity in your tests.

