1. Set up the development environment:

To start the development of the healthcare management system, first set up the development environment. Install Visual Studio, .NET Core SDK, and MySQL Server on your development machine.

2. Create a new ASP.NET Core Web Application

Open Visual Studio and create a new ASP.NET Core Web Application. Name the project HealthcareManagementSystem. Select the Web Application template and make sure to check the "Enable Docker Support" and "Configure for HTTPS" options.

3. Install NuGet packages

Install the following NuGet packages:

- Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore
- Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Design
- Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Tools
- Pomelo.EntityFrameworkCore.MySql
- AutoMapper.Extensions.Microsoft.DependencyInjection
- Swashbuckle.AspNetCore

4. Set up the Database

First, create a new MySQL database for the healthcare management system. Then, add the connection string to the appsettings.json file of your ASP.NET Core project.

```
{
  "ConnectionStrings": {
    "DefaultConnection": "server=localhost;database=HealthcareManagementSystem;user=root;password=your_password;"
  },
  ...
}
```

5. Create Models and DbContext

Create the following models: Patient, Appointment, Medication, and HealthcareFacility. Then, create the HealthcareDbContext class that inherits from DbContext and configure your models and database provider.

```csharp
protected override void OnConfiguring(DbContextOptionsBuilder optionsBuilder)
{
    optionsBuilder.UseMySql(Configuration.GetConnectionString("DefaultConnection"),
        MariaDbServerVersion.LatestSupportedServerVersion);
}
```

6. Apply Database Migrations

In the Package Manager Console, execute the following commands to create and apply migrations:

```
Add-Migration InitialCreate
Update-Database
```

7. Create Repository and Service Layer

Create repository classes for each model (e.g., PatientRepository, AppointmentRepository, MedicationRepository) and corresponding service classes (i.e., PatientService, AppointmentService, MedicationService) that use the repositories to interact with the database.

8. Set up REST Controllers

Create REST API Controllers (e.g., PatientsController, AppointmentsController, MedicationsController) that expose Create, Read, Update, and Delete (CRUD) operations for each resource. Use dependency injection to inject the corresponding services.

9. Set up AutoMapper

Create AutoMapper profiles for each of the models:

```csharp
public class PatientProfile : Profile
{
    public PatientProfile()
    {
        CreateMap<Patient, PatientDto>().ReverseMap();
    }
}

public class AppointmentProfile : Profile
{
    public AppointmentProfile()
    {
        CreateMap<Appointment, AppointmentDto>().ReverseMap();
    }
}
```

10. Integrate with Google Maps

To integrate the healthcare management system with Google Maps, follow these steps:

- Retrieve API Key from the Google Cloud Platform Console.
- Install the NuGet package GoogleMaps.LocationServices.
- Create a new `LocationService` and inject it into the `HealthcareFacilityController`.
- Add a new REST endpoint that uses the `LocationService` to retrieve directions between two points.

11. Set up Swagger

In the Startup.cs file, configure the Swagger middleware in the ConfigureServices method:

```csharp
services.AddSwaggerGen(c =>
{
    c.SwaggerDoc("v1", new OpenApiInfo { Title = "Healthcare Management System API", Version = "v1" });
});
```

And in the Configure method:

```csharp
app.UseSwagger();
app.UseSwaggerUI(c =>
{
    c.SwaggerEndpoint("/swagger/v1/swagger.json", "Healthcare Management System API v1");
});
```

12. Run and Test the Application

Now you can run the application and test the REST endpoints using a tool like Postman or simply opening Swagger UI in your browser.

With these steps, you should have a basic healthcare management system using ASP.NET Core, REST services, Entity Framework, and MySQL. You can further enhance the application by implementing authentication and authorization, and adding more features based on the requirements.

